\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.1}{\ignorespaces The OASG in practice (left): observed SOC appears above the 20\% safety floor while the true SOC has already breached it. DC3S detects reliability degradation, inflates the safety margin, and intercepts the unsafe action before dispatch. The DC3S five-stage pipeline (right) maps the live OQE reliability score $w_t$ through calibrated uncertainty inflation (RUI), tightened action constraints (SAF), safe-action repair, and auditable runtime certificates (CERTos).}}{3}{figure.caption.6}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.1}{\ignorespaces Empirical OASG rate (TSVR) versus dropout rate for the deterministic LP. Non-zero TSVR at all $d > 0$ confirms Theorem~\ref {thm:oasg-existence}.}}{51}{figure.caption.40}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.2}{\ignorespaces P95 violation severity versus dropout rate. The DC3S shield (blue) achieves zero severity across all dropout rates, confirming Theorem~\ref {thm:safety-preservation}.}}{56}{figure.caption.43}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.3}{\ignorespaces Empirical TSVR (markers) versus the ORIUS Core Bound (dashed line) as a function of average reliability $\bar {w}$. All empirical points lie below the bound.}}{63}{figure.caption.51}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.4}{\ignorespaces P95 violation severity for quality-ignorant controllers (LP, CQR-only) versus DC3S across dropout rates. Quality-ignorant controllers exhibit non-zero severity at all $d > 0$, confirming Theorem~\ref {thm:no-free-safety}.}}{69}{figure.caption.59}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.5}{\ignorespaces Coverage--width tradeoff under temporal extension. As the certificate ages (horizontal axis), the coverage probability decreases while the interval width increases. The half-life (vertical dashed line) marks the crossover point.}}{75}{figure.caption.69}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.1}{\ignorespaces True-state violation rate versus dropout rate. DC3S (blue) remains at zero across the full sweep.}}{99}{figure.caption.94}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.2}{\ignorespaces 48-hour operational trace (DE, \texttt {drift\_combo}, dropout~0.20). Top: dispatch power (LP request in red, DC3S safe action in blue). Bottom: true SOC (black) with observed SOC (grey dashed) and constraint bounds (shaded).}}{141}{figure.caption.104}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.3}{\ignorespaces TSVR heatmap across the hyperparameter sweep. DC3S achieves 0.00\% TSVR at every tested grid point.}}{142}{figure.caption.108}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.4}{\ignorespaces Intervention rate heatmap across the hyperparameter sweep. DC3S+FTIT IR ranges from 0.0\% to 5.4\%.}}{142}{figure.caption.109}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.5}{\ignorespaces Coverage vs.\ interval width across volatility groups. RAC-Cert inflation widens intervals for under-covered subgroups.}}{143}{figure.caption.113}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.6}{\ignorespaces Four-policy graceful-degradation comparison. The current locked battery trace differentiates the policies primarily by useful work retained and descent quality, not by observed safety loss in the measured horizon.}}{143}{figure.caption.122}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.7}{\ignorespaces CertOS lifecycle state machine as implemented in the battery runtime. The defended contract is precise: remain in valid or degraded certified execution when a horizon exists; otherwise fall back explicitly.}}{144}{figure.caption.128}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.8}{\ignorespaces No-action-without-certificate runtime path. A release path exists only for certified actions; otherwise the runtime records a fallback event and emits the fallback action instead.}}{144}{figure.caption.132}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.1}{\ignorespaces ORIUS universal 5-stage pipeline. Each domain plugs in a \texttt {DomainAdapter}; the DC3S core (stages 1--5) is shared and domain-agnostic.}}{148}{figure.caption.137}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.2}{\ignorespaces Universal ORIUS validation surface across all six domains. Each bar pair shows unshielded TSVR (before shield) and DC3S TSVR (after shield) under the unified fault schedule. All six domains achieve sub-$\alpha $ violations post-shield, with DC3S providing equivalent safety guarantees regardless of domain physics.}}{152}{figure.caption.147}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.3}{\ignorespaces Cross-domain validation surface from the canonical universal evidence tier table. The labels encode the defended claim boundary: reference, proof-validated, proof-candidate, shadow-synthetic, and experimental.}}{153}{figure.caption.149}%
